{"title_page": "1818 in poetry", "text_new": "{{Year nav topic5|1818|poetry|literature}}\n\n{{cquote|A thing of beauty is a joy for ever:\nIts loveliness increases; it will never<br />\nPass into nothingness;}}\n:::::::\u2014 [[John Keats]], ''[[Endymion (poem)|Endymion]]''\n\nNationality words link to articles with information on the nation's poetry or literature (for instance, [[Irish poetry|Irish]] or [[French poetry|France]]).\n\n==Events==\n\n===John Keats===\n* June&ndash;August &ndash; [[John Keats|Keats]] with his friend [[Charles Armitage Brown]] makes a walking tour of [[Scotland]], Ireland and the English [[Lake District]]. On July 11 while in Scotland he visits [[Burns Cottage]], the birthplace of [[Robert Burns]] in [[1759 in poetry|1759]]. Before Keats arrives, he writes to a friend that \"one of the pleasantest means of annulling self is approaching such a shrine as the cottage of Burns \u2014 we need not think of his misery \u2014 that is all gone \u2014 bad luck to it \u2014 I shall look upon it all with unmixed pleasure.\"<ref name=rckhr/> but his encounter with the cottage's alcoholic custodian returns him to thoughts of misery.<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=Sidney Colvin|first=Sidney|last=Colvin|title=John Keats}}</ref> On August 2 he climbs to the summit of [[Ben Nevis]], on which he writes a sonnet.<ref>{{cite web|title=200 years ago Keats climbed Ben Nevis|work=Keats 200|url=http://johnkeats200.co.uk/1818/200-years-ago-keats-climbed-ben-nevis/|date=2018|accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* September&ndash;November &ndash; Keats meets and falls in love with [[Fanny Brawne]] (1800&ndash;65).<ref>{{cite book|last=Gittings|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Gittings|year=1968|title=John Keats|location=London|publisher=Heinemann|page=262}}</ref> \n* December &ndash; Keats is invited to move into Brown's home at [[Keats House|Wentworth Place]], in [[Hampstead]], at this time a pastoral suburb north of London. In the next 17 months as Brown's housemate, Keats writes \"[[Ode on a Grecian Urn]]\", \"[[The Eve of St. Agnes]]\" and \"[[Ode to a Nightingale]]\", among other works.<ref name=rckhr>Costa, Robert, [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204886304574308681606221044 \"Keats\u2019s House, Restored\"], article, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', August 4, 2009, retrieved August 12, 2009. [https://www.webcitation.org/5j3Blm6oc?url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052970204886304574308681606221044.html Archived] 2009-08-15.</ref>\n\n===Other events===\n* January 11 &ndash; [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]]'s \"[[Ozymandias]]\" is published in Leigh Hunt's weekly ''[[The Examiner (1808\u201386)|The Examiner]]'' (London; p.&nbsp;24) under the pen name 'Glirastes'; [[Horace Smith (poet)|Horace Smith]]'s contribution to the same informal [[sonnet]]-writing competition, \"On a Stupendous Leg of Granite, Discovered Standing by Itself in the Deserts of Egypt, with the Inscription Inserted Below\" is published on February 1 under his initials.\n* February 4 &ndash; While [[John Keats]] and [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]] are at [[James Henry Leigh Hunt|Leigh Hunt]]'s home for the evening, all three compete in composing sonnets about the Nile. Hunt is judged the winner, with:<ref>Jones, Neal T. (ed.), ''A Book of Days for the Literary Year'', New York; London: Thames and Hudson (1984), unpaginated, {{ISBN|0-500-01332-2}}.</ref>\n:::''It flows through old hushed Egypt and its sands,\n:::''Like some grave mighty thought threading a dream,\n:::''And times and things, as in that vision, seem\n:::''Keeping along it their eternal stands'' [...]\n* March 12 &ndash; [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]] and family, along with his sister-in-law [[Claire Clairmont]], mother of [[Lord Byron|Lord Byron's]] child, leaves England for the Continent, reaching Milan April 4 and visiting the Italian lakes. In June they move to the Bagni di Lucca, where Shelley translates Plato's ''[[Symposium]]'', writes \"On Love,\" and completes ''[[Rosalind and Helen]]''. In August, they move to Este, near Venice to be closer to [[Lord Byron]]; there Shelley begins ''Prometheus Unbound.'' Their daughter Clara dies September 24 and the Shelleys visit Venice October 12\u2013[[October 31|31]], then travel to Rome and Naples, where they remain until February 28, 1819.\n* September 19 &ndash; [[Lord Byron]] writes to [[Thomas Moore]], telling him he has completed the first Canto of ''[[Don Juan (Byron)|Don Juan]]'' (which he began on July 3).<ref>[http://lordbyron.cath.lib.vt.edu/monograph.php?doc=ThMoore.1830&select=AD1818 Letter CCCXXII.]</ref>\n\n==Works published==\n\n===[[English poetry|United Kingdom]]===\n<blockquote style=\"float:right; border:1px solid gray; padding:2em 1em; margin: 0 0 1em 1em; text-align:left; background:lightyellow;\"><!--\n    ACTUAL SPELLING FROM EARLIEST PUBLICATIONS: please do not add apocryphal Caps or \"upon\"\n--><div style=\"text-align:center;\">'''[[Ozymandias]]'''<br/>By [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]]</div>\n<poem>I met a traveller from an antique land\nWho said: Two vast and trunkless legs of stone\nStand in the desert. Near them, on the sand,\nHalf sunk, a shattered visage lies, whose frown\nAnd wrinkled lip, and sneer of cold command\nTell that its sculptor well those passions read\nWhich yet survive, stamped on these lifeless things,\nThe hand that mocked them and the heart that fed.\nAnd on the pedestal these words appear:\n\"My name is Ozymandias, king of kings:\nLook on my works, ye Mighty, and despair!\"\nNothing beside remains.  Round the decay\nOf that colossal wreck, boundless and bare\nThe lone and level sands stretch far away.<ref>Text of the poem from {{cite book|title=Rosalind and Helen, a modern eclogue, with other poems|first=Percy Bysshe|last=Shelley|year=1819|publisher=C. and J. Ollier|location=London|oclc=1940490|url=https://archive.org/details/rosalindhelenmod00she }} and {{cite book|title=Miscellaneous and posthumous poems of Percy Bysshe Shelley|first=Percy Bysshe|last=Shelley|publisher=W. Benbow|year=1826|location=London|oclc=13349932|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MZY9AAAAYAAJ }}. The two texts are identical except that in the earlier \"desert\" is spelled \"desart\".</ref></poem></blockquote>\n* [[Bernard Barton]]:\n**''The Convict's Appeal''<ref name=cocel>{{cite book|editor=Cox, Michael|title=The Concise Oxford Chronology of English Literature|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2004|isbn=0-19-860634-6|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/conciseoxfordchr00coxm}}</ref>\n**''Poems'', anonymously published as \"by an amateur\"<ref name=cocel/>\n* [[Thomas Haynes Bayly]], published under the [[pen name]] \"Q. in the Corner\", ''Parliamentary Letters, and Other Poems''<ref name=cocel/>\n* [[Mary Matilda Betham]], ''Vignettes''<ref name=cocel/>\n* [[William Blake]], ''[[Jerusalem The Emanation of the Giant Albion]]'', illuminated book of 100 plates, estimated to have been published this date, although \"[[1804 in poetry|1804]]\" is printed on the title plate, but \"this probably indicates the date when Blake began the work\"<ref name=cocel/>\n* Sir [[Thomas Burges]], ''The Dragon Knight''<ref name=cocel/>\n* [[Lord Byron]]:\n** ''Beppo: A Venetian story'', published anonymously<ref name=cocel/>\n** ''Childe Harold's Pilgrimage: Canto the Fourth'' (see also ''Child Harold'', [[1812 in poetry|1812]], [[1816 in poetry|1816]])<ref name=cocel/>\n* [[William Hazlitt]], ''Lectures on the English Poets'' (criticism)\n* [[Felicia Dorothea Hemans]], ''Translations from Camoens and Other Poets, with Original Poetry''<ref name=cocel/>\n* [[James Henry Leigh Hunt|Leigh Hunt]]:\n** ''Foliage; or, Poems Original and Translated''<ref name=cocel/>\n** ''Literary Pocket-Book'' (miscellaneous poetry and prose)<ref name=cocel/>\n* [[John Keats]]:\n** ''[[Endymion (poem)|Endymion]]''\n** \"[[When I have Fears that I may Cease to Be]]\"\n* [[Thomas Moore]], publishing as \"Thomas Brown the Younger\", ''The Fudge Family in Paris'', at least nine editions published this year<ref name=cocel/>\n* [[Hannah More]], ''Tragedies''<ref name=cocel/>\n* [[Thomas Love Peacock]], ''Rhododaphne; or, The Thessalian Spell''<ref name=cocel/>\n* [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]]:\n** ''[[Julian and Maddalo]]''\n** ''[[Ozymandias]]''\n* [[William Sotheby]], ''Farewell to Italy, and Occasional Poems''<ref name=cocel/>\n\n===[[American poetry|United States]]===\n* [[Phoebe Hinsdale Brown]], \"[[I love to steal awhile away]]\", American religious hymn<ref name=\"FahySociety2005\">{{cite book|last1=Fahy|first1=Lynn Kloter|last2=Society|first2=The Ellington Historical|title=Ellington|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uFmaliBi-DUC&pg=PA45|year=2005|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|isbn=978-0-7385-3824-2|pages=45\u2013}}</ref>\n* [[William Cullen Bryant]], ''To a Waterfowl''<ref name=rmlaal>Ludwig, Richard M.; Nault, Jr., Clifford A., ''Annals of American Literature, 1602\u20131983'', 1986, New York: Oxford University Press (\"If the title page is one year later than the copyright date, we used the latter since publishers frequently postdate books published near the end of the calendar year.\" \u2014 from the Preface, p vi.)</ref>\n* [[Thomas Green Fessenden]], ''The ladies monitor, a poem'' (Bellows Falls: Printed by Bill Blake & Co.)<ref name=ucapb>{{cite web|url=https://www.lib.uchicago.edu/efts/AmPo1/AmPo.bib.html|title=American Poetry Full-Text Database - Bibliography|publisher=University of Chicago Library|accessdate=2009-03-04}}</ref>\n* [[John Neal (writer)|John Neal]]:\n** ''The Portico'' Volume 3 (Baltimore: Neale Wills & Cole)<ref name=ucapb/>\n** ''Battle of Niagara''<ref name=rmlaal/>\n** ''Goldau, or, the Maniac Harper''<ref name=rmlaal/>\n* [[James Kirke Paulding]], ''The Backwoodsman'' (Philadelphia: M. Thomas),<ref name=ucapb/><ref name=gceafd>{{cite book|last=Carruth|first=Gorton|title=The Encyclopedia of American Facts and Dates|url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofam00carr_1|url-access=registration|edition=9th|publisher=HarperCollins|year=1993}}</ref> a long poem in heroic couplets about a New York pioneer on the frontier in Kentucky<ref name=dbcal>Burt, Daniel S., [https://books.google.com/books?id=VQ0fgo5v6e0C ''The Chronology of American Literature: America's literary achievements from the colonial era to modern times''], Houghton Mifflin Harcourt, 2004, {{ISBN|978-0-618-16821-7}}, retrieved via Google Books.</ref>\n* [[Samuel Woodworth]], ''The Poems, Odes, Songs, and Other Metrical Effusions, of Samuel Woodworth'' (New York: Abraham Asten and Matthias Lopez)<ref name=ucapb/>\n* [[Richard Henry Wilde]], \"My Life is Like the Summer Rose\", [[John Greenleaf Whittier]] called it \"a perfect poem\"<ref name=ldrtls>Rubin, Louis D., Jr., ''The Literary South'', John Wiley & Sons, 1979, {{ISBN|0-471-04659-0}}.</ref>\n\n==Works misdated as this year==\n* [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]], ''[[The Revolt of Islam]]'', originally ''Laon and Cythna'' (actually printed in December [[1817 in poetry|1817]] although the book states the year of publication as this year)<ref name=cocel/>\n\n==Works published in other languages==\n* [[Kristijonas Donelaitis]], ''[[The Seasons (poem)|The Seasons]]'' (\"Metai\" in [[Lithuanian literature|Lithuanian]]), written about 1765\u20131775, is published in [[K\u00f6nigsberg]]\n* [[Adam Mickiewicz]], ''City Winter'' (\"Zima miejska\" in [[Polish poetry|Polish]]), his first poem, is published in [[Vilnius]]\n\n==Births==\nDeath years link to the corresponding \"[year] in poetry\" article:\n* January 24 \u2013 [[John Mason Neale]], [[English poetry|English]] priest, scholar and hymnwriter (died [[1866 in poetry|1866]])\n* April \u2013 [[Cecil Frances Alexander]], n\u00e9e Humphreys, Anglo-[[Irish poetry|Irish]] hymnwriter (died [[1895 in poetry|1895]])\n* July 30 \u2013 [[Emily Bront\u00eb]], [[English poetry|English]] novelist and poet (died [[1848 in poetry|1848]])\n* October 16 \u2013 [[William Forster (Australian politician)|William Forster]], [[Australian poetry|Australian]] politician, Premier of New South Wales and poet (died [[1882 in poetry|1882]])\n* October 22 \u2013 [[Leconte de Lisle]], [[French poetry|French]] Parnassian poet (died [[1894 in poetry|1894]])\n* December 24 \u2013 [[Eliza Cook]], [[English poetry|English]] writer, poet and radical campaigner (died [[1889 in poetry|1889]])\n*Date unknown:\n** [[Alexander McLachlan (poet)|Alexander McLachlan]], [[Scottish poetry|Scottish]]-born [[Canadian poetry|Canadian]] poet (died [[1896 in poetry|1896]])\n** [[Charlotta \u00d6berg]], [[Swedish poetry|Swedish]] poet (died [[1856 in poetry|1856]])\n\n==Deaths==\nBirth years link to the corresponding \"[year] in poetry\" article:\n* May 14 or 16 \u2013 [[Matthew Lewis (writer)|Matthew Lewis]], [[English poetry|English]] Gothic writer (born [[1775 in poetry|1775]])\n* November 23 \u2013 [[John Williams (satirist)|John Williams]], [[English poetry|English]] satirist, journalist and poet, in the United States (born [[1761 in poetry|1716]])\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Poetry}}\n* [[Poetry]]\n* [[List of years in poetry]]\n* [[List of years in literature]]\n* [[19th century in literature]]\n* [[19th century in poetry]]\n* [[Romantic poetry]]\n* [[Golden Age of Russian Poetry]] (1800\u20131850)\n* [[Weimar Classicism]] period in [[German poetry|Germany]], commonly considered to have begun in 1788 and to have ended either in 1805, with the death of [[Friedrich Schiller]], or 1832, with the death of [[Johann von Goethe|Goethe]]\n* [[List of poets]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Poetry of different cultures and languages}}\n{{Lists of poets}}\n\n[[Category:1818|Poetry]]\n[[Category:1818 poems|*]]\n[[Category:19th-century poetry]]\n", "text_old": "{{Year nav topic5|1818|poetry|literature}}\n\n{{cquote|A thing of beauty is a joy for ever:\nIts loveliness increases; it will never<br />\nPass into nothingness;}}\n:::::::\u2014 [[John Keats]], ''[[Endymion (poem)|Endymion]]''\n\nNationality words link to articles with information on the nation's poetry or literature (for instance, [[Irish poetry|Irish]] or [[French poetry|France]]).\n\n==Events==\n\n===John Keats===\n* June&ndash;August &ndash; [[John Keats|Keats]] with his friend [[Charles Armitage Brown]] makes a walking tour of [[Scotland]], Ireland and the [[Lake District]]. On July 11 while in Scotland he visits [[Burns Cottage]], the birthplace of [[Robert Burns]] in [[1759 in poetry|1759]]. Before Keats arrives, he writes to a friend that \"one of the pleasantest means of annulling self is approaching such a shrine as the cottage of Burns \u2014 we need not think of his misery \u2014 that is all gone \u2014 bad luck to it \u2014 I shall look upon it all with unmixed pleasure.\"<ref name=rckhr/> but his encounter with the cottage's alcoholic custodian returns him to thoughts of misery.<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=Sidney Colvin|first=Sidney|last=Colvin|title=John Keats}}</ref> On August 2 he climbs to the summit of [[Ben Nevis]], on which he writes a sonnet.<ref>{{cite web|title=200 years ago Keats climbed Ben Nevis|work=Keats 200|url=http://johnkeats200.co.uk/1818/200-years-ago-keats-climbed-ben-nevis/|date=2018|accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* September&ndash;November &ndash; Keats meets and falls in love with [[Fanny Brawne]] (1800&ndash;65).<ref>{{cite book|last=Gittings|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Gittings|year=1968|title=John Keats|location=London|publisher=Heinemann|page=262}}</ref> \n* December &ndash; Keats is invited to move into Brown's home at [[Keats House|Wentworth Place]], in [[Hampstead]], at this time a pastoral suburb north of London. In the next 17 months as Brown's housemate, Keats writes \"[[Ode on a Grecian Urn]]\", \"[[The Eve of St. Agnes]]\" and \"[[Ode to a Nightingale]]\", among other works.<ref name=rckhr>Costa, Robert, [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204886304574308681606221044 \"Keats\u2019s House, Restored\"], article, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', August 4, 2009, retrieved August 12, 2009. [https://www.webcitation.org/5j3Blm6oc?url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052970204886304574308681606221044.html Archived] 2009-08-15.</ref>\n\n===Other events===\n* January 11 &ndash; [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]]'s \"[[Ozymandias]]\" is published in Leigh Hunt's weekly ''[[The Examiner (1808\u201386)|The Examiner]]'' (London; p.&nbsp;24) under the pen name 'Glirastes'; [[Horace Smith (poet)|Horace Smith]]'s contribution to the same informal [[sonnet]]-writing competition, \"On a Stupendous Leg of Granite, Discovered Standing by Itself in the Deserts of Egypt, with the Inscription Inserted Below\" is published on February 1 under his initials.\n* February 4 &ndash; While [[John Keats]] and [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]] are at [[James Henry Leigh Hunt|Leigh Hunt]]'s home for the evening, all three compete in composing sonnets about the Nile. Hunt is judged the winner, with:<ref>Jones, Neal T. (ed.), ''A Book of Days for the Literary Year'', New York; London: Thames and Hudson (1984), unpaginated, {{ISBN|0-500-01332-2}}.</ref>\n:::''It flows through old hushed Egypt and its sands,\n:::''Like some grave mighty thought threading a dream,\n:::''And times and things, as in that vision, seem\n:::''Keeping along it their eternal stands'' [...]\n* March 12 &ndash; [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]] and family, along with his sister-in-law [[Claire Clairmont]], mother of [[Lord Byron|Lord Byron's]] child, leaves England for the Continent, reaching Milan April 4 and visiting the Italian lakes. In June they move to the Bagni di Lucca, where Shelley translates Plato's ''[[Symposium]]'', writes \"On Love,\" and completes ''[[Rosalind and Helen]]''. In August, they move to Este, near Venice to be closer to [[Lord Byron]]; there Shelley begins ''Prometheus Unbound.'' Their daughter Clara dies September 24 and the Shelleys visit Venice October 12\u2013[[October 31|31]], then travel to Rome and Naples, where they remain until February 28, 1819.\n* September 19 &ndash; [[Lord Byron]] writes to [[Thomas Moore]], telling him he has completed the first Canto of ''[[Don Juan (Byron)|Don Juan]]'' (which he began on July 3).<ref>[http://lordbyron.cath.lib.vt.edu/monograph.php?doc=ThMoore.1830&select=AD1818 Letter CCCXXII.]</ref>\n\n==Works published==\n\n===[[English poetry|United Kingdom]]===\n<blockquote style=\"float:right; border:1px solid gray; padding:2em 1em; margin: 0 0 1em 1em; text-align:left; background:lightyellow;\"><!--\n    ACTUAL SPELLING FROM EARLIEST PUBLICATIONS: please do not add apocryphal Caps or \"upon\"\n--><div style=\"text-align:center;\">'''[[Ozymandias]]'''<br/>By [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]]</div>\n<poem>I met a traveller from an antique land\nWho said: Two vast and trunkless legs of stone\nStand in the desert. Near them, on the sand,\nHalf sunk, a shattered visage lies, whose frown\nAnd wrinkled lip, and sneer of cold command\nTell that its sculptor well those passions read\nWhich yet survive, stamped on these lifeless things,\nThe hand that mocked them and the heart that fed.\nAnd on the pedestal these words appear:\n\"My name is Ozymandias, king of kings:\nLook on my works, ye Mighty, and despair!\"\nNothing beside remains.  Round the decay\nOf that colossal wreck, boundless and bare\nThe lone and level sands stretch far away.<ref>Text of the poem from {{cite book|title=Rosalind and Helen, a modern eclogue, with other poems|first=Percy Bysshe|last=Shelley|year=1819|publisher=C. and J. Ollier|location=London|oclc=1940490|url=https://archive.org/details/rosalindhelenmod00she }} and {{cite book|title=Miscellaneous and posthumous poems of Percy Bysshe Shelley|first=Percy Bysshe|last=Shelley|publisher=W. Benbow|year=1826|location=London|oclc=13349932|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MZY9AAAAYAAJ }}. The two texts are identical except that in the earlier \"desert\" is spelled \"desart\".</ref></poem></blockquote>\n* [[Bernard Barton]]:\n**''The Convict's Appeal''<ref name=cocel>{{cite book|editor=Cox, Michael|title=The Concise Oxford Chronology of English Literature|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2004|isbn=0-19-860634-6|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/conciseoxfordchr00coxm}}</ref>\n**''Poems'', anonymously published as \"by an amateur\"<ref name=cocel/>\n* [[Thomas Haynes Bayly]], published under the [[pen name]] \"Q. in the Corner\", ''Parliamentary Letters, and Other Poems''<ref name=cocel/>\n* [[Mary Matilda Betham]], ''Vignettes''<ref name=cocel/>\n* [[William Blake]], ''[[Jerusalem The Emanation of the Giant Albion]]'', illuminated book of 100 plates, estimated to have been published this date, although \"[[1804 in poetry|1804]]\" is printed on the title plate, but \"this probably indicates the date when Blake began the work\"<ref name=cocel/>\n* Sir [[Thomas Burges]], ''The Dragon Knight''<ref name=cocel/>\n* [[Lord Byron]]:\n** ''Beppo: A Venetian story'', published anonymously<ref name=cocel/>\n** ''Childe Harold's Pilgrimage: Canto the Fourth'' (see also ''Child Harold'', [[1812 in poetry|1812]], [[1816 in poetry|1816]])<ref name=cocel/>\n* [[William Hazlitt]], ''Lectures on the English Poets'' (criticism)\n* [[Felicia Dorothea Hemans]], ''Translations from Camoens and Other Poets, with Original Poetry''<ref name=cocel/>\n* [[James Henry Leigh Hunt|Leigh Hunt]]:\n** ''Foliage; or, Poems Original and Translated''<ref name=cocel/>\n** ''Literary Pocket-Book'' (miscellaneous poetry and prose)<ref name=cocel/>\n* [[John Keats]]:\n** ''[[Endymion (poem)|Endymion]]''\n** \"[[When I have Fears that I may Cease to Be]]\"\n* [[Thomas Moore]], publishing as \"Thomas Brown the Younger\", ''The Fudge Family in Paris'', at least nine editions published this year<ref name=cocel/>\n* [[Hannah More]], ''Tragedies''<ref name=cocel/>\n* [[Thomas Love Peacock]], ''Rhododaphne; or, The Thessalian Spell''<ref name=cocel/>\n* [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]]:\n** ''[[Julian and Maddalo]]''\n** ''[[Ozymandias]]''\n* [[William Sotheby]], ''Farewell to Italy, and Occasional Poems''<ref name=cocel/>\n\n===[[American poetry|United States]]===\n* [[Phoebe Hinsdale Brown]], \"[[I love to steal awhile away]]\", American religious hymn<ref name=\"FahySociety2005\">{{cite book|last1=Fahy|first1=Lynn Kloter|last2=Society|first2=The Ellington Historical|title=Ellington|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uFmaliBi-DUC&pg=PA45|year=2005|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|isbn=978-0-7385-3824-2|pages=45\u2013}}</ref>\n* [[William Cullen Bryant]], ''To a Waterfowl''<ref name=rmlaal>Ludwig, Richard M.; Nault, Jr., Clifford A., ''Annals of American Literature, 1602\u20131983'', 1986, New York: Oxford University Press (\"If the title page is one year later than the copyright date, we used the latter since publishers frequently postdate books published near the end of the calendar year.\" \u2014 from the Preface, p vi.)</ref>\n* [[Thomas Green Fessenden]], ''The ladies monitor, a poem'' (Bellows Falls: Printed by Bill Blake & Co.)<ref name=ucapb>{{cite web|url=https://www.lib.uchicago.edu/efts/AmPo1/AmPo.bib.html|title=American Poetry Full-Text Database - Bibliography|publisher=University of Chicago Library|accessdate=2009-03-04}}</ref>\n* [[John Neal (writer)|John Neal]]:\n** ''The Portico'' Volume 3 (Baltimore: Neale Wills & Cole)<ref name=ucapb/>\n** ''Battle of Niagara''<ref name=rmlaal/>\n** ''Goldau, or, the Maniac Harper''<ref name=rmlaal/>\n* [[James Kirke Paulding]], ''The Backwoodsman'' (Philadelphia: M. Thomas),<ref name=ucapb/><ref name=gceafd>{{cite book|last=Carruth|first=Gorton|title=The Encyclopedia of American Facts and Dates|url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofam00carr_1|url-access=registration|edition=9th|publisher=HarperCollins|year=1993}}</ref> a long poem in heroic couplets about a New York pioneer on the frontier in Kentucky<ref name=dbcal>Burt, Daniel S., [https://books.google.com/books?id=VQ0fgo5v6e0C ''The Chronology of American Literature: America's literary achievements from the colonial era to modern times''], Houghton Mifflin Harcourt, 2004, {{ISBN|978-0-618-16821-7}}, retrieved via Google Books.</ref>\n* [[Samuel Woodworth]], ''The Poems, Odes, Songs, and Other Metrical Effusions, of Samuel Woodworth'' (New York: Abraham Asten and Matthias Lopez)<ref name=ucapb/>\n* [[Richard Henry Wilde]], \"My Life is Like the Summer Rose\", [[John Greenleaf Whittier]] called it \"a perfect poem\"<ref name=ldrtls>Rubin, Louis D., Jr., ''The Literary South'', John Wiley & Sons, 1979, {{ISBN|0-471-04659-0}}.</ref>\n\n==Works misdated as this year==\n* [[Percy Bysshe Shelley]], ''[[The Revolt of Islam]]'', originally ''Laon and Cythna'' (actually printed in December [[1817 in poetry|1817]] although the book states the year of publication as this year)<ref name=cocel/>\n\n==Works published in other languages==\n* [[Kristijonas Donelaitis]], ''[[The Seasons (poem)|The Seasons]]'' (\"Metai\" in [[Lithuanian literature|Lithuanian]]), written about 1765\u20131775, is published in [[K\u00f6nigsberg]]\n* [[Adam Mickiewicz]], ''City Winter'' (\"Zima miejska\" in [[Polish poetry|Polish]]), his first poem, is published in [[Vilnius]]\n\n==Births==\nDeath years link to the corresponding \"[year] in poetry\" article:\n* January 24 \u2013 [[John Mason Neale]], [[English poetry|English]] priest, scholar and hymnwriter (died [[1866 in poetry|1866]])\n* April \u2013 [[Cecil Frances Alexander]], n\u00e9e Humphreys, Anglo-[[Irish poetry|Irish]] hymnwriter (died [[1895 in poetry|1895]])\n* July 30 \u2013 [[Emily Bront\u00eb]], [[English poetry|English]] novelist and poet (died [[1848 in poetry|1848]])\n* October 16 \u2013 [[William Forster (Australian politician)|William Forster]], [[Australian poetry|Australian]] politician, Premier of New South Wales and poet (died [[1882 in poetry|1882]])\n* October 22 \u2013 [[Leconte de Lisle]], [[French poetry|French]] Parnassian poet (died [[1894 in poetry|1894]])\n* December 24 \u2013 [[Eliza Cook]], [[English poetry|English]] writer, poet and radical campaigner (died [[1889 in poetry|1889]])\n*Date unknown:\n** [[Alexander McLachlan (poet)|Alexander McLachlan]], [[Scottish poetry|Scottish]]-born [[Canadian poetry|Canadian]] poet (died [[1896 in poetry|1896]])\n** [[Charlotta \u00d6berg]], [[Swedish poetry|Swedish]] poet (died [[1856 in poetry|1856]])\n\n==Deaths==\nBirth years link to the corresponding \"[year] in poetry\" article:\n* May 14 or 16 \u2013 [[Matthew Lewis (writer)|Matthew Lewis]], [[English poetry|English]] Gothic writer (born [[1775 in poetry|1775]])\n* November 23 \u2013 [[John Williams (satirist)|John Williams]], [[English poetry|English]] satirist, journalist and poet, in the United States (born [[1761 in poetry|1716]])\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Poetry}}\n* [[Poetry]]\n* [[List of years in poetry]]\n* [[List of years in literature]]\n* [[19th century in literature]]\n* [[19th century in poetry]]\n* [[Romantic poetry]]\n* [[Golden Age of Russian Poetry]] (1800\u20131850)\n* [[Weimar Classicism]] period in [[German poetry|Germany]], commonly considered to have begun in 1788 and to have ended either in 1805, with the death of [[Friedrich Schiller]], or 1832, with the death of [[Johann von Goethe|Goethe]]\n* [[List of poets]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Poetry of different cultures and languages}}\n{{Lists of poets}}\n\n[[Category:1818|Poetry]]\n[[Category:1818 poems|*]]\n[[Category:19th-century poetry]]\n", "name_user": "Camboxer", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eJohn Keats:location clarified", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1818_in_poetry"}
{"title_page": "Parkway Parade", "text_new": "{{coord|1|18|07|N|103|54|17|E|display=title}}\n{{Use Singapore English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox shopping mall\n  | name              = Parkway Parade <br><small> \u767e\u6c47\u5e7f\u573a <br> \u0baa\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bc7 \u0b85\u0ba3\u0bbf\u0bb5\u0b95\u0bc1\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1</small>\n  | image             = Parkway Parade.JPG\n  | caption           = \n  | location          = [[Marine Parade]], [[Singapore]]\n  | address           = 80 Marine Parade Road\n  | opening_date      = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1983|12}}\n  | developer         = [[Parkway Holdings]]\n  | manager           = [[Lendlease]]\n  | owner             = Parkway Parade is a mixed-use development with sub-divided strata ownership. It is owned by Parkway Parade Partnership Limited fund managed by Lend Lease.\n  | number_of_stores  = 270\n  | number_of_anchors = 7\n  | floor_area        = {{convert|561000|sqft|m2}}\n  | floors            = 7\n  | website           = {{url|www.parkwayparade.com.sg}}\n  | parking           = 1,201 (including 6 handicap and 3 green lots)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.parkwayparade.com.sg/en/centre%20information/parking%20services | title=Parking Services | work=Parkway Parade | accessdate=5 November 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Parkway Parade''' is a [[suburb]]an [[shopping mall|shopping centre]] in [[Marine Parade]], [[Singapore]].<ref name=\"mypaper2\">{{cite news| title = It's a MALL world after all | author = Cheong Suk-Wai | newspaper = [[The Straits Times|The Sunday Times]] | location = Singapore | date = 2 April 2006 | page = | accessdate = | language = }}</ref> Officially opened on 9 March 1984, it has a 17-floor office tower and a seven-storey shopping mall with a basement. Developed by [[Parkway Holdings]], the company sold the building to Asia Pacific Investment Company in 2000. The mall is managed by [[Lendlease]].\n\n==History==\nParkway Parade was developed by Parkway Holdings and was completed in December 1983. At that time of completion, it was one of the first suburban shopping malls in Singapore. It featured many major tenants setting up their stores in the suburbs for the first time, such as Isetan, Marks and Spencer, Yaohan Best, children's department store Small World and MPH Bookstores. It also featured a wide array of food choices, including Chuck'E'Cheese, Hardees', and Petite Park. The mall also had an amusement centre occupying Levels 3 and 4 (Funland) and a playground at Level 7, which was the largest mall playground in Singapore at that time.\n\nIn 2000, the property was sold to Asia Pacific Insurance Company, and subsequently Lendlease was appointed to manage the mall.\n\nThe mall commenced its first makeover in March 2002 and was completed in two phases. The first phase included a new tenant mix, to reflect the positioning of the mall. This included anchor tenant, [[Giant Hypermarket|Giant]], occupying nearly half of the third floor. The mall's second phase was completed in November 2003, with a brand-new and expanded [[food court]] at the Basement floor and an [[Al fresco dining|alfresco]]-dining area on the first floor. It also included the completion of the 'Waterfall' leisure and dining precinct with one of the country's tallest glass waterfall, a water play area, six food and beverage outdoor kiosks and a restaurant. The mall was fully renovated in November 2003.\n\nFurther facelifts were done to mall's exterior featuring an expanded [[Al fresco dining|alfresco]]-dining to the first floor. in 2011, with the removal of the 'Waterfall' leisure feature and repositioning of the entrance area. Completed in end 2012, the new [[Al fresco dining|alfresco]]-dining area houses around 10 new tenants to the expansion, which includes Din Tai Fung, Papparich and Twelve Cupcakes.\n\nIn 2015, another round of renovations were made to keep the mall updated. Best Denki was relocated to Level 3, together with six rows of retail shops taking a part of Giant Hypermarket's space. [[Cathay Cineplexes]] opened in September 2017, taking over the former True Fitness space at Level 7.<ref>[https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/cathay-cinema-to-open-in-parkway-parade Cathay Cineplexes opens at Parkway Parade]</ref>\n\nGiant has ceased operations after an 18-year tenancy at Parkway Parade in March 2020.<ref>[https://goodyfeed.com/giant-parkway-parade-closure Iconic Giant supermarket in Parkway Parade will be closing; last day on 29 Feb]</ref>\n[[File:Parkway Parade 7, Dec 05.JPG|thumb|175px|center|Parkway Parade Shopping Centre]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.parkwayparade.com.sg}}\n\n{{Singapore malls}}\n\n[[Category:1984 establishments in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Shopping malls in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Marine Parade]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord|1|18|07|N|103|54|17|E|display=title}}\n{{Use Singapore English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox shopping mall\n  | name              = Parkway Parade <br><small> \u767e\u6c47\u5e7f\u573a <br> \u0baa\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bc7 \u0b85\u0ba3\u0bbf\u0bb5\u0b95\u0bc1\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1</small>\n  | image             = Parkway Parade.JPG\n  | caption           = \n  | location          = [[Marine Parade]], [[Singapore]]\n  | address           = 80 Marine Parade Road\n  | opening_date      = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1983|12}}\n  | developer         = [[Parkway Holdings]]\n  | manager           = [[Lendlease]]\n  | owner             = Parkway Parade is a mixed-use development with sub-divided strata ownership. It is owned by Parkway Parade Partnership Limited fund managed by Lend Lease.\n  | number_of_stores  = 270\n  | number_of_anchors = 7\n  | floor_area        = {{convert|561000|sqft|m2}}\n  | floors            = 7\n  | website           = {{url|www.parkwayparade.com.sg}}\n  | parking           = 1,201 (including 6 handicap and 3 green lots)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.parkwayparade.com.sg/en/centre%20information/parking%20services | title=Parking Services | work=Parkway Parade | accessdate=5 November 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Parkway Parade''' is a [[suburb]]an [[shopping mall|shopping centre]] in [[Marine Parade]], [[Singapore]].<ref name=\"mypaper2\">{{cite news| title = It's a MALL world after all | author = Cheong Suk-Wai | newspaper = [[The Straits Times|The Sunday Times]] | location = Singapore | date = 2 April 2006 | page = | accessdate = | language = }}</ref> Officially opened on 9 March 1984, it has a 17-floor office tower and a seven-storey shopping mall with a basement. Developed by [[Parkway Holdings]], the company sold the building to Asia Pacific Investment Company in 2000. The mall is managed by [[Lendlease]].\n\n==History==\nParkway Parade was developed by Parkway Holdings and was completed in December 1983. At that time of completion, it was one of the first suburban shopping malls in Singapore. It featured many major tenants setting up their stores in the suburbs for the first time, such as Isetan, Marks and Spencer, Yaohan Best, children's department store Small World and MPH Bookstores. It also featured a wide array of food choices, including Chuck'E'Cheese, Hardees', and Petite Park. The mall also had an amusement centre occupying Levels 3 and 4 (Funland) and a playground at Level 7, which was the largest mall playground in Singapore at that time.\n\nIn 2000, the property was sold to Asia Pacific Insurance Company, and subsequently Lendlease was appointed to manage the mall.\n\nThe mall commenced its first makeover in March 2002 and was completed in two phases. The first phase included a new tenant mix, to reflect the positioning of the mall. This included anchor tenant, [[Giant Hypermarket|Giant]], occupying nearly half of the third floor. The mall's second phase was completed in November 2003, with a brand-new and expanded [[food court]] at the Basement floor and an [[Al fresco dining|alfresco]]-dining area on the first floor. It also included the completion of the 'Waterfall' leisure and dining precinct with one of the country's tallest glass waterfall, a water play area, six food and beverage outdoor kiosks and a restaurant. The mall was fully renovated in November 2003.\n\nFurther facelifts were done to mall's exterior featuring an expanded [[Al fresco dining|alfresco]]-dining to the first floor. in 2011, with the removal of the 'Waterfall' leisure feature and repositioning of the entrance area. Completed in end 2012, the new [[Al fresco dining|alfresco]]-dining area houses around 10 new tenants to the expansion, which includes Din Tai Fung, Papparich and Twelve Cupcakes.\n\nIn 2015, another round of renovations were made to keep the mall updated. Best Denki was relocated to Level 3, together with six rows of retail shops taking a part of Giant Hypermarket's space. [[Cathay Cineplexes]] opened in September 2017, taking over the former True Fitness space at Level 7.<ref>[https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/cathay-cinema-to-open-in-parkway-parade Cathay Cineplexes opens at Parkway Parade]</ref>\n\nGiant has ceased operations after an 18-year tenancy at Parkway Parade in March 2020.<ref>[https://goodyfeed.com/giant-parkway-parade-closure Iconic Giant supermarket in Parkway Parade will be closing; last day on 29 Feb]</ref>\n[[File:Parkway Parade 7, Dec 05.JPG|thumb|175px|center|Parkway Parade Shopping Centre]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.parkwayparade.com.sg}}\n\n{{Singapore malls}}\n\n[[Category:Shopping malls in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Marine Parade]]\n", "name_user": "TheGreatSG'rean", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parkway_Parade"}
{"title_page": "Hagit Attiya", "text_new": "{{short description|Israeli computer scientist}}\n'''Hagit Attiya''' is an Israeli [[computer scientist]] who holds the Harry W. Labov and Charlotte Ullman Labov Academic Chair of Computer Science at the [[Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology]] in [[Haifa]], [[Israel]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.focus.technion.ac.il/May11/womenStory4.asp|title=The Female Postdoc's Guide to the Galaxy|journal=Focus: E-mag of the Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology|date=May 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"cv\" /> Her research is in the area of [[distributed computing]].\n\n==Education and career==\nAttiya was educated at the [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]], earning a B.S. in mathematics and computer science in 1981, a master's degree from the same university in 1983, and a doctorate in 1987, under the supervision of [[Danny Dolev]].<ref name=\"cv\">[https://www.cs.technion.ac.il/~hagit/cv.pdf Curriculum vitae], retrieved 2014-07-07.</ref> After postdoctoral studies at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], she joined the Technion faculty in 1990.<ref name=\"cv\" />\n\nShe has been the [[editor-in-chief]] of the [[scientific journal|journal]] ''[[Distributed Computing (journal)|Distributed Computing]]'' since 2008.<ref name=\"cv\" /><ref>[https://www.springer.com/computer/communication+networks/journal/446?detailsPage=editorialBoard ''Distributed Computing'' editorial board], retrieved 2014-07-07.</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nAttiya became a [[fellow]] of the [[Association for Computing Machinery]] in 2009 for \"contributions to distributed and parallel computing\".<ref>[http://awards.acm.org/award_winners/attiya_3834843.cfm [[List of Fellows of the Association for Computing Machinery|ACM Fellow]] citation], retrieved 2014-07-07.</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Attiya and her co-authors [[Danny Dolev]] and Amotz Bar-Noy won the [[Dijkstra Prize|Edsger W. Dijkstra Prize in Distributed Computing]] for their work on implementing [[Shared memory architecture|shared memory]] using [[message passing]], published in the [[Journal of the ACM]] in 1995.<ref>[https://www.cs.technion.ac.il/news/2011/465/docs/paper.pdf 2011 Edsger W. Dijkstra Prize in Distributed Computing], [[Technion]], retrieved 2014-07-07.</ref> She was also the recipient of the [[Michael Bruno]] Memorial Award from [[Yad Hanadiv]] in 2011.<ref>[http://www.yadhanadiv.org.il/recipient/hagit-attiya Michael Bruno Memorial Award: Hagit Attiya, Computer Sciences 2011], Yad Hanadiv, retrieved 2014-07-07.</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n;Research papers\n*{{citation\n| last1 = Attiya | first1 = Hagit\n| last2 = Bar-Noy | first2 = Amotz\n| last3 = Dolev | first3 = Danny\n| last4 = Peleg | first4 = David\n| last5 = Reischuk | first5 = R\u00fcdiger\n| date = July 1990\n| doi = 10.1145/79147.79158\n| issue = 3\n| journal = [[Journal of the ACM]]\n| pages = 524\u2013548\n| title = Renaming in an Asynchronous Environment\n| volume = 37\n}}\n*{{citation\n| last1 = Afek | first1 = Yehuda\n| last2 = Attiya | first2 = Hagit\n| last3 = Dolev | first3 = Danny | author3-link = Danny Dolev\n| last4 = Gafni | first4 = Eli\n| last5 = Merritt | first5 = Michael\n| last6 = Shavit | first6 = Nir\n| date = September 1993\n| doi = 10.1145/153724.153741\n| issue = 4\n| journal = [[Journal of the ACM]]\n| pages = 873\u2013890\n| title = Atomic Snapshots of Shared Memory\n| url = http://people.csail.mit.edu/shanir/publications/AADGMS.pdf\n| volume = 40\n}}\n*{{citation\n| last1 = Attiya | first1 = Hagit\n| last2 = Bar-Noy | first2 = Amotz\n| last3 = Dolev | first3 = Danny | author3-link = Danny Dolev\n| date = January 1995\n| doi = 10.1145/200836.200869\n| issue = 1\n| journal = [[Journal of the ACM]]\n| pages = 124\u2013142\n| title = Sharing Memory Robustly in Message-passing Systems\n| url = http://www.cse.huji.ac.il/course/2004/dist/p124-attiya.pdf\n| volume = 42\n}}\n\n;Books\n*{{citation\n| last1 = Attiya | first1 = Hagit\n| last2 = Welch | first2 = Jennifer\n| edition = 2nd\n| isbn = 978-0-471-45324-6\n| location = Hoboken, NJ | publisher = Wiley | year = 2004\n| title = Distributed Computing: Fundamentals, Simulations, and Advanced Topics\n}}<ref name=\"herlihy\" /><ref name=\"ieee\" />\n*{{citation\n| last1 = Attiya | first1 = Hagit\n| last2 = Ellen | first2 = Faith | author2-link = Faith Ellen\n| title = Impossibility Results for Distributed Computing (Synthesis Lectures on Distributed Computing Theory)\n| location = San Rafael, CA | publisher = Morgan & Claypool | year = 2014\n| isbn = 9781627051712\n<!-- | pages = 1\u2013162 is the entire book. -->\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"herlihy\">{{citation\n| last = Herlihy | first = Maurice | authorlink = Maurice Herlihy\n| date = March 2000\n| doi = 10.1145/346048.568464\n| volume = 31 | issue = 1\n| journal = [[SIGACT News]]\n| page = 3\n| title = Review of Distributed Computing by Attiya and Welch\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ieee\">{{citation\n| title = Mastering distributed computing\n| last = Che | first = Haoyang\n| journal = IEEE Distributed Systems Online\n| volume = 6 | issue = 3\n| pages = 5\n| date = March 2005\n| doi = 10.1109/MDSO.2005.14\n}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.cs.technion.ac.il/~hagit/ Home page]\n*{{google scholar id|eoMK92MAAAAJ}}\n\n{{Authority_Control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Attiya, Hagit}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Israeli computer scientists]]\n[[Category:Israeli women computer scientists]]\n[[Category:Researchers in distributed computing]]\n[[Category:Hebrew University of Jerusalem alumni]]\n[[Category:Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Association for Computing Machinery]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Israeli computer scientist}}\n'''Hagit Attiya''' is an Israeli [[computer scientist]] who holds the Harry W. Labov and Charlotte Ullman Labov Academic Chair of Computer Science at the [[Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology]] in [[Haifa]], [[Israel]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.focus.technion.ac.il/May11/womenStory4.asp|title=The Female Postdoc's Guide to the Galaxy|journal=Focus: E-mag of the Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology|date=May 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"cv\" /> Her research is in the area of [[distributed computing]].\n\n==Education and career==\nAttiya was educated at the [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]], earning a B.S. in mathematics and computer science in 1981, a master's degree from the same university in 1983, and a doctorate in 1987, under the supervision of [[Danny Dolev]].<ref name=\"cv\">[https://www.cs.technion.ac.il/~hagit/cv.pdf Curriculum vitae], retrieved 2014-07-07.</ref> After postdoctoral studies at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], she joined the Technion faculty in 1990.<ref name=\"cv\" />\n\nShe has been the [[editor-in-chief]] of the [[scientific journal|journal]] ''[[Distributed Computing (journal)|Distributed Computing]]'' since 2008.<ref name=\"cv\" /><ref>[https://www.springer.com/computer/communication+networks/journal/446?detailsPage=editorialBoard ''Distributed Computing'' editorial board], retrieved 2014-07-07.</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nAttiya became a [[fellow]] of the [[Association for Computing Machinery]] in 2009 for \"contributions to distributed and parallel computing\".<ref>[http://awards.acm.org/award_winners/attiya_3834843.cfm [[List of Fellows of the Association for Computing Machinery|ACM Fellow]] citation], retrieved 2014-07-07.</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Attiya and her co-authors [[Danny Dolev]] and Amotz Bar-Noy won the [[Dijkstra Prize|Edsger W. Dijkstra Prize in Distributed Computing]] for their work on implementing [[Shared memory architecture|shared memory]] using [[message passing]], published in the [[Journal of the ACM]] in 1995.<ref>[https://www.cs.technion.ac.il/news/2011/465/docs/paper.pdf 2011 Edsger W. Dijkstra Prize in Distributed Computing], [[Technion]], retrieved 2014-07-07.</ref> She was also the recipient of the [[Michael Bruno]] Memorial Award from [[Yad Hanadiv]] in 2011.<ref>[http://www.yadhanadiv.org.il/recipient/hagit-attiya Michael Bruno Memorial Award: Hagit Attiya, Computer Sciences 2011], Yad Hanadiv, retrieved 2014-07-07.</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n;Research papers\n*{{citation\n| last1 = Attiya | first1 = Hagit\n| last2 = Bar-Noy | first2 = Amotz\n| last3 = Dolev | first3 = Danny\n| last4 = Peleg | first4 = David\n| last5 = Reischuk | first5 = R\u00fcdiger\n| date = July 1990\n| doi = 10.1145/79147.79158\n| issue = 3\n| journal = [[Journal of the ACM]]\n| pages = 524\u2013548\n| title = Renaming in an Asynchronous Environment\n| volume = 37\n}}\n*{{citation\n| last1 = Afek | first1 = Yehuda\n| last2 = Attiya | first2 = Hagit\n| last3 = Dolev | first3 = Danny | author3-link = Danny Dolev\n| last4 = Gafni | first4 = Eli\n| last5 = Merritt | first5 = Michael\n| last6 = Shavit | first6 = Nir\n| date = September 1993\n| doi = 10.1145/153724.153741\n| issue = 4\n| journal = [[Journal of the ACM]]\n| pages = 873\u2013890\n| title = Atomic Snapshots of Shared Memory\n| url = http://people.csail.mit.edu/shanir/publications/AADGMS.pdf\n| volume = 40\n}}\n*{{citation\n| last1 = Attiya | first1 = Hagit\n| last2 = Bar-Noy | first2 = Amotz\n| last3 = Dolev | first3 = Danny | author3-link = Danny Dolev\n| date = January 1995\n| doi = 10.1145/200836.200869\n| issue = 1\n| journal = [[Journal of the ACM]]\n| pages = 124\u2013142\n| title = Sharing Memory Robustly in Message-passing Systems\n| url = http://www.cse.huji.ac.il/course/2004/dist/p124-attiya.pdf\n| volume = 42\n}}\n\n;Books\n*{{citation\n| last1 = Attiya | first1 = Hagit\n| last2 = Welch | first2 = Jennifer\n| edition = 2nd\n| isbn = 978-0-471-45324-6\n| location = Hoboken, NJ | publisher = Wiley | year = 2004\n| title = Distributed Computing: Fundamentals, Simulations, and Advanced Topics\n}}<ref name=\"herlihy\" /><ref name=\"ieee\" />\n*{{citation\n| last1 = Attiya | first1 = Hagit\n| last2 = Ellen | first2 = Faith | author2-link = Faith Ellen\n| title = Impossibility Results for Distributed Computing (Synthesis Lectures on Distributed Computing Theory)\n| location = San Rafael, CA | publisher = Morgan & Claypool | year = 2014\n| isbn = 9781627051712\n<!-- | pages = 1\u2013162 is the entire book. -->\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"herlihy\">{{citation\n| last = Herlihy | first = Maurice | authorlink = Maurice Herlihy\n| date = March 2000\n| doi = 10.1145/346048.568464\n| volume = 31 | issue = 1\n| journal = [[SIGACT News]]\n| page = 3\n| title = Review of Distributed Computing by Attiya and Welch\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ieee\">{{citation\n| title = Mastering distributed computing\n| last = Che | first = Haoyang\n| journal = IEEE Distributed Systems Online\n| volume = 6 | issue = 3\n| pages = 5\n| date = March 2005\n| doi = 10.1109/MDSO.2005.14\n}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.cs.technion.ac.il/~hagit/ Home page]\n*[https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=eoMK92MAAAAJ Google scholar profile]\n\n{{Authority_Control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Attiya, Hagit}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Israeli computer scientists]]\n[[Category:Israeli women computer scientists]]\n[[Category:Researchers in distributed computing]]\n[[Category:Hebrew University of Jerusalem alumni]]\n[[Category:Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Association for Computing Machinery]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Kj cheetham", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:google scholar id", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hagit_Attiya"}
{"title_page": "Gateforth", "text_new": "{{Short description|Village and civil parish in North Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country                  = England\n|static_image             = Gateforth Village Green - geograph.org.uk - 113992.jpg\n|static_image_width       = 220px\n|static_image_caption     = Gateforth Village Green\n|population               = 240\n|coordinates              = {{coord|53.75164|-1.15499|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name            = Gateforth\n|civil_parish             = Gateforth\n|shire_district           = [[Selby (district)|Selby]]\n|shire_county             = [[North Yorkshire]]\n|region                   = Yorkshire and the Humber\n|post_town                = SELBY\n|postcode_district        = YO8\n|postcode_area            = YO\n|dial_code                = 01757\n|os_grid_reference        = SE557286\n}}\n'''Gateforth''' is a small village and [[civil parish]] located in [[North Yorkshire]], England. The village is {{Convert|4|mi|0}} south west of the town of [[Selby]] and {{Convert|1.4|mi|0}} south of the village of [[Hambleton, Selby|Hambleton]], where a shop and three pubs are located. Gateforth is approximately {{convert|20|mi|km|0}} east of [[Leeds]]. According to the [[2011 UK census]], the village had a population of 240 with 94 households.<ref>{{cite web|work=Neighbourhood Statistics |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11123681&c=Gateforth&d=16&e=62&g=6455595&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1388529105618&enc=1 |title=Key Figures for 2011 Census: Key Statistics Area: Gateforth (Parish)  |publisher=Office for National Statistics |date= |accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Notable buildings==\n[[File:Gateforth Hall Hotel - geograph.org.uk - 107800.jpg|thumb|Gateforth Hall|left]]\nGateforth Hall was built in 1812 by influential local landowner Sir Humphrey Brooke Osbaldeston \u2013 at one time sheriff of [[York]] \u2013 and used as a meet for Bramham Moor Hunt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/place/12699 |title=History of Gateforth, in Selby and West Riding &#124; Map and description |publisher=Visionofbritain.org.uk |date= |accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"yorkshireeveningpost\">{{cite news|author= |url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/what-s-on/restaurant-martel-at-gateforth-hall-1-2075173 |title=Restaurant Martel at Gateforth Hall |work=Yorkshire Evening Post |date=5 September 2001 |accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref> Subsequently it was used as a hospital for [[tuberculosis]] patients and later a restaurant.<ref name=\"yorkshireeveningpost\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/domesday/dblock/GB-452000-429000/page/18 |title=Domesday Reloaded: GATEFORTH HALL |publisher=BBC |date= |accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref> As of 2013, it was for sale as a house.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zoopla.co.uk/for-sale/details/29515793 |title=7 bedroom detached house for sale in Gateforth Hall, Gateforth, North Yorkshire YO8 - 29515793 |publisher=Zoopla |date= |accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref> It is a [[Listed building|Grade II* listed]] building.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-325896-gateforth-hall-gateforth-north-yorkshire |title=Gateforth Hall - Gateforth - North Yorkshire - England |publisher=British Listed Buildings |date= |accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref>\nOther notable listed buildings on the former Gateforth Hall estate include a [[ha-ha]] (landscape feature) in the grounds and the coach house.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/england/north+yorkshire/gateforth |title=Listed Buildings in Gateforth, North Yorkshire, England |publisher=British Listed Buildings |date= |accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref>\nSelby Golf Club is located {{Convert|2|mi|0}} north east of Gateforth. The 71 par course was established as a club in 1907.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.selbygolfclub.co.uk/ |title=Limited |publisher=Selby Golf Club |date= |accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hambleton, Selby|Hambleton]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060111130035/http://www.selby.gov.uk/parish_main.asp?id=38 Gateforth Parish Council]\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Civil parishes in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Selby District]]\n[[Category:Villages in North Yorkshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Village and civil parish in North Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country                  = England\n|static_image             = Gateforth Village Green - geograph.org.uk - 113992.jpg\n|static_image_width       = 220px\n|static_image_caption     = Gateforth Village Green\n|population               = 240\n|coordinates              = {{coord|53.75164|-1.15499|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name            = Gateforth\n|civil_parish             = Gateforth\n|shire_district           = [[Selby (district)|Selby]]\n|shire_county             = [[North Yorkshire]]\n|region                   = Yorkshire and the Humber\n|post_town                = SELBY\n|postcode_district        = YO8\n|postcode_area            = YO\n|dial_code                = 01757\n|os_grid_reference        = SE557286\n}}\n'''Gateforth''' is a small village and [[civil parish]] located in [[North Yorkshire]], England. The village is {{Convert|4|mi|0}} south west of the town of [[Selby]] and {{Convert|1.4|mi|0}} south of the village of [[Hambleton, Selby|Hambleton]], where a shop and three pubs are located. Gateforth is approximately {{convert|20|mi|km|0}} east of [[Leeds]]. According to the [[2011 UK census]], the village had a population of 240 with 94 households.<ref>{{cite web|work=Neighbourhood Statistics |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11123681&c=Gateforth&d=16&e=62&g=6455595&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1388529105618&enc=1 |title=Key Figures for 2011 Census: Key Statistics Area: Gateforth (Parish)  |publisher=Office for National Statistics |date= |accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Notable buildings ==\n[[File:Gateforth Hall Hotel - geograph.org.uk - 107800.jpg|thumb|Gateforth Hall|left]]\nGateforth Hall was built in 1812 by influential local landowner Sir Humphrey Brooke Osbaldeston \u2013 at one time sheriff of [[York]] \u2013 and used as a meet for Bramham Moor Hunt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/place/12699 |title=History of Gateforth, in Selby and West Riding &#124; Map and description |publisher=Visionofbritain.org.uk |date= |accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"yorkshireeveningpost\">{{cite news|author= |url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/what-s-on/restaurant-martel-at-gateforth-hall-1-2075173 |title=Restaurant Martel at Gateforth Hall |work=Yorkshire Evening Post |date=5 September 2001 |accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref> Subsequently it was used as a hospital for [[tuberculosis]] patients and later a restaurant.<ref name=\"yorkshireeveningpost\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/domesday/dblock/GB-452000-429000/page/18 |title=Domesday Reloaded: GATEFORTH HALL |publisher=BBC |date= |accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref> As of 2013, it was for sale as a house.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zoopla.co.uk/for-sale/details/29515793 |title=7 bedroom detached house for sale in Gateforth Hall, Gateforth, North Yorkshire YO8 - 29515793 |publisher=Zoopla |date= |accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref> It is a [[Listed building|Grade II* listed]] building.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-325896-gateforth-hall-gateforth-north-yorkshire |title=Gateforth Hall - Gateforth - North Yorkshire - England |publisher=British Listed Buildings |date= |accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref>\nOther notable listed buildings on the former Gateforth Hall estate include a [[ha-ha]] (landscape feature) in the grounds and the coach house.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/england/north+yorkshire/gateforth |title=Listed Buildings in Gateforth, North Yorkshire, England |publisher=British Listed Buildings |date= |accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref>\nSelby Golf Club is located {{Convert|2|mi|0}} north east of Gateforth. The 71 par course was established as a club in 1907.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.selbygolfclub.co.uk/ |title=Limited |publisher=Selby Golf Club |date= |accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Hambleton, Selby|Hambleton]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060111130035/http://www.selby.gov.uk/parish_main.asp?id=38 Gateforth Parish Council]\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Civil parishes in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Selby District]]\n[[Category:Villages in North Yorkshire]]\n", "name_user": "Indoreli", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gateforth"}
